Statements

Daniel Kitachewsky

Entered By: Daniel Kitachewsky 		In round 4, Carlos is playing against Cesar Olvera Castellanos. Carlos is facing the clock, Cesar has the clock behind him. Carlos claims it's turn 5 and he would lose on turn 6 if there was one. Cesar wasn't aware that the players were in turns. When questioned, Carlos had a consistent story (with some hesitations) about how each turn since time was called unfolded. However there had already been 10-12 minutes of questioning by the first FJ (Antonio Zanutto) and another (Adrian Estoup). Carlos said to the first judge that he wasn't sure of the turns. He then said to the second judge that he told his opponent "now it's turns" (which Cesar denies). Carlos was not keeping track of the turns with dice or paper and said he was tracking them in his head. I decided that too many details were shady and disqualified Carlos for lying, as I thought that either he was not aware of the turns and later backtracked them, or was lying about telling his opponent it was turns. In addition, his stories told to Antonio and Adrian didn't match. Finally, his only way of winning the game was not to give his opponent another turn. In the end, I'm about 80% sure it was correct to DQ, but am not certain about what exactly happened. There is definitely room for the player being perfectly conscious of his actions and that he engineered the number of turns a few minutes after time was called, although that's pretty advanced. It's also possible he really was counting turns in his head; it was strange though that he claimed mentioning turns which the opponent denied. I don't feel too bad about it though, as he had multiple chances to keep a clean game state but took none of them.

Unfortunately I forgot to ask the opponent for statement.

Adrian Estoup

Entered By: Daniel Kitachewsky 		During GP Mexico, Antonio Zanutto requested my help for a investigation.
Basically we was out of time counting turns and I arrived at the table to know the situation. This was the argument of each player:
Player A "We was playing and at some point, the judge asked to us how what number of turn we was playing. At this moment I realized we was in turns. My opponents said "this in the turn 5" but He never said nothing related the time over and from my position, I can't see the watch"
Player B "When the judge arrived he asked us "what turn are you playing" and I respond "this is the turn 5". When the judge made the announcement I said to my opponent "turn 0""
Looking this situation I checked the cards in play, hands and life totals. Player A had several creatures in play and Player B had only lands. However, the Player A will not win by combat damage because Player B life total was near to 20.
During investigations I trust about the argument of Player B but in some point i was not comfortable about some arguments. For this reason I decided call Daniel to involve him on the investigation.
During the investigation, the Player B explain us the perfect history but was unable to probe his argument.

Antonio Zanutto

Entered By: Daniel Kitachewsky 		It was 7 minutes passed time was called for the round and I was doing end of round procedures (looking for tables and watching the games for slow play/stalling) and I came up to two players that were still playing and I asked them "what turn is this?" and both players answered me "turns?" then I asked them "do you know time was called in the round?" in which Cesar answered me "I wasn't paying attention, I didn't hear anything" and Carlos just nodded. I told them it is extremely important to be paying attention to announcements and that it was not okay to disregard this. Cesar insisted that he didn't hear anything while Carlos told me "this should be turn five, yeah, I remember when he called time and I started counting" and I asked him "did you tell your opponent that?" in which he shook his head and Cesar told me "no".
At that moment Adrian Estoup arrived and started asking the players a few questions, after they answer him I pull Adrian aside and tell him "by his body expression, I believe he is lying". A couple of minutes latter the Head Judge Daniel arrives at the table and start an investigation, in which Carlos is telling a completely different story then what he told me, now he is saying "I told him when time was called and I started counting turns and this is turn five". As I believed he was trying to gain advantage on his match with his story and he was also lying to a Judge, I asked Daniel to talk to me and I explain him all that have happened since I arrived at the table.
Daniel asked Carlos a few more questions and finally concluded that he was lying to a Judge to gain advantage, thus, was DQd from the event.

Daniel Kitachewsky

Entered By: Daniel Kitachewsky 		To whoever it may concern, by the present I'm explaining my case; what happened is the following: in round 3 (sic) of Grand Prix Mexico 2015, the score was 1-1, we were starting the game with just 2 minutes on the clock until extra turns, we start the game and when time was called I told my opponent he was the active player and we continued playing; I was counting the turns however my mistake was not tallying them or counting them physically. When the judge came and asked us which turn we were in my opponent said he didn't know we were in extra turns and he didn't heard any announcement about it and I told the judge that I thought we were in turn 5, but my opponent wasn't agreeing and that was a pretext to call 3 different judges and getting different stories at the end of which the final judge decided to disqualify me for lying about knowing about the turns whereas I knew them although my opponent had more creatures and I had no reason to lie. My fury is that really I didn't care about drawing of losing I just came to have fun this was my first GP.
(translated from original Spanish by Daniel. Some words were hard to make out, so I sent a picture of the statement to Eric Shukan.
A quien corresponda, por medio de la presente hago este escrito para explicar mi caso, la cosa paso asi: en el evento del gran prix Mexico 2015, en la ronda 3 jugaba y el marcador era 1 a 1, estabamos empezando la ronda comtan solo 2 minutos restante en el reloj para los tornos, empezamos a jugar y cuando dijieron turnos yo lo compate a mi oponente que el era el jugador activo y seguimos jugando, yo contaba los turnos pero mi error fue no apuntarlos o contarlos fisicamente y cuando llego el juez nos pregunta que ronda era en ese momento le comento el jugador oponente que nos sabia que no habia escuchado que dijeran tornos en ese momento yo le dije al juez que penseria que esta el turno 5 pero creendo el jugador contrario no estubo de acuerdo fue cuando yo le afirme que si era el turno 5 y pues eso agarro de pretexta mi oponente lo cual llevaron a llamar a 3 jueces diferentes y sacar diferentes historias el cual el ultime juez tomo la decision de descalificarme del evento por que le menti al juez diciendo yo no sabia cuando si y por como estaba la mesa que mi oponente renia mas criaturas en ese momento y yo no tenia por mentir. Mi furor, y es que la verdad no me importaba empatar o perder solo vine a divertirme es mi primer gran prix.)
